`sed -i 's/EXTRA_OPERATORS =/EXTRA_OPERATORS = example\/rcnn\/operator/g' config.mk && \`

According to your workflow, I have check the code, and found these lines (342-343 in model.py for saving models). It seems that MXNet try to save (trained) model into CPU format.
```python
    save_dict = {('arg:%s' % k) : v.as_in_context(cpu()) for k, v in arg_params.items()}
    save_dict.update({('aux:%s' % k) : v.as_in_context(cpu()) for k, v in aux_params.items()})
```
When you try to  load existing model, if compiled with CUDA, i.e, GPU enabled. MXNet will convert it from CPU format to GPU format.
```cpp
  if (ctx.dev_mask() == cpu::kDevMask) {
    *this = std::move(temp); return true;
  } else {
#if MXNET_USE_CUDA
    *this = temp.Copy(ctx); return true;
#else
    *this = std::move(temp); return true;
#endif
```

Here is a workflow. 

**Save model:**
Train a model, then model.save()-> NDarray GPU ->convert to NDarray CPU->files->Done

**Load model:**
model.load from files->NDarray CPU->NDarray GPU->Done

In my opinion, your model is not saved correctly. For example, maybe you have saved it manually into GPU format. Then, when you try to load it, you will get an error.

